after my sister got married, well - you know what it, when you get a man you get a master. So when my sister got married that was me, I was - bunkered then at the post as they say in Leith, well I went into lodgings - and I - I got my wages up, I had eigh
t and fourpence a week. I paid five shillings for my lodging, kept myself in my own clothes, and my pocket money things like that, and the lady I lived with - she stayed down in - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}West Bowling Green{\*\xmlclose}
. Well I used to chum about - with her wee girls then, we j
ust - we were just working in the mill, and I used to chum about with them. So - I went to stay with her. And many a time I would go home and wash, help her out, and she'd maybe buy me a wee blouse or - pair of shoes or a pair of stockings. Well that woma
n's daughter still lives - in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Bangor Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} yet, the top of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
