\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid605028 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 How long was he there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5585082 SO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 Oh about thirty years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid605028 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 Did he do anything else after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5585082 SO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 
Yes. He'd never go idle my husband if possible, and - when the shipping was bad he would just take a job, he 
worked with ICI for a wee while, in between you know, if there were any - if the shipping was bad, and they weren't - couldn't get a ship for a bit, he never went idle if he could help it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid605028 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 What sort of job would he do with ICI?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5585082 SO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 Well that's a manure works. Carrying or shoveling, I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid605028 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 Just casual labourer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5585082 SO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 
Aye. Just casual labourer. But if - in fact I've got his shipping books there to this day. And I've got his - I've got his - records for the time that he was on the Aberdeen boats, still have them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid605028 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 What other sort of jobs would he take in between?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5585082 SO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 
That was nearly all that ever he done, but - when he's - chest started to trouble him - and he stopped going to sea, to tell you the truth he stopped going to sea after I l
ost my second girl. He thought I - I'll stay at home. He felt this coming back, there was always another one and - I'll stay at home here for a while. Well - he sort of went down because I think once a sailor always a sailor. I think he wearied to get bac
k to sea. But however - I - as I say, I worked in hotels. And remember one time we were awful busy, I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12852251\charrsid12863516 charge hand}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516  in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12852251\charrsid12863516 George}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516  Hotel, and we were awful busy, and the boss came to me and he says to me, Mrs Scott I hope you can bring a few helpers in ton
ight. There's a rugby match I think. So - I said I wonder what we'll do, well Kenny, my son, came up, and my hubby wasna at work at that time, he says, I'll come up and give you a hand. I says, well - so he came up and there were two or three of my girls 
-
 pals round about, neighbour, looking for the extra money. Well a while after that he came in a couple of times in the hotel to help us out, my husband. And one day the manager sent for me and he says, Mrs Scott, about that - elder man that comes up, mind
 
not - not the young ones. He says, do you think he would take a job here? I says, oh I'm not so sure. Whether he would take a job here or not. But I said - and you see, in the hotel men'll come the night and work, and get the price of a bed sort of style 
a
nd they're away. Get a feed. Maybe - come strangers, up and on like that you know. So, he says to me - do you think he would take a job? He says, it's to help in the stores. So I said, well of course you'll understand that he's not supposed to take a heav
y job just now. I says I'll ask him and see. He says, well - I says, and if he has to leave in a few days, don't put him in the category of these men, I says, for I wouldn't work here for a lazy husband. He says, oh it's your husband? I says, aye, I }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12852251\charrsid12863516 didn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 '
 know. So he didna know then. Well he was there eighteen year. Just like left there - retired from there when he died. Eighteen year he was there. And always called him the sailor.
\par 
