\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5585082 SO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 Oh aye. Walked like h
im and all. Oh yes, they used to say - and - and - the manager said to me, he's an old sailor isn't he? I said, yes. He says, well - and he was very handy for the boilers, if anything went wrong, he was the handyman there. He went into the stores and he w
a
s only about three weeks in the stores. And they asked him one day if he'd wash a few pots, and - I remember he says to me, I've washed pots. He says, I'm going to do it, he says, I'm not above it, he says, but I wouldna - he thought he was going to be ke
p
t there. But however they asked him if he would take the handyman job and that's what he done. He went to the rooms, changed the furniture, put up the curtains, took - carried the laundry down. If you were ordering a room that you wanted two single beds h
e
'd put the two single beds in. All these sort of things. And he was there for eighteen year. I remember - when he died, he's buried across the road there - the hotel sent him a - an anchor, och, big as that. And - flowers, and the very rope - was through 
it. Always called him the old - sailor. And he was there eighteen years, so that's where we finished up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid605028 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 You worked after you were married, did your husband mind you working or not?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5585082 SO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 No. He didna mind me working when he knew that it was to help ou
t. He didna like it. Didna like me working at first. But - when he came home - with his wages, well with what he'd have left, and I'd go out and have the children to get shoes and things like that I never had - had anything left. And it was a case that - 
when he come home when I did start to work, always had what I needed for the children. Used to go down sometimes round the shore and meet him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid605028 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 How about your husband's work, do you think he liked being a sailor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5585082 SO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 Oh aye. Oh - they were all seamen.
 His mother - came to - Scotland to put them all in a trade, and they were all in a trade. All left one after the other and took to sea. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid605028 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 
You had nine children. Can you tell me the dates of birth of those born before the end of 1918? Your first one was born at the end of 1912?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5585082 SO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 1912. 1914. And - 19 - Kenneth, 1918. Uh huh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid605028 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 Were your children born at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5585082 SO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 Yes. Bar - Kenneth. 'Cos as I say I was in Glasgow. Aye, that's right.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid605028 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 Did you know what to expect when you were having 
the children? Had anyone told you what to expect?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5585082 SO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 
Not the first one. I didn't know a thing. I hadn't a thing to put on the child. And I had the money lying there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid605028 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 Your mother-in-law had never told you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5585082 SO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 Well - it may have - it may have emba
rrassed me if she spoke to me. See? My - own sister, not interrupting you, came up one day to take me out, and she stopped - at a baby linen shop, and she was telling me, she says, you'll have to be getting this Sarah, you'll have to be getting that, and 
I
 fell out with her. I thought she'd no right - to speak in that manner to me. And I come home and I was sitting crying when my husband came in. He wasn't as tall as that. He says what's the matter with you? Are you not feeling well? I telled him, he said 
- he was as daft as I was of course, he says, oh I'll see her, I'll tell her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid605028 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 And she was just wanting to help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5585082 SO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 Uh huh. You see, now they can just - talk. They didna bother now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid605028 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 Did you have any medical help, a doctor or a midwife?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5585082 SO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 Aye, well I - had the medical then off the nurses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid605028 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 Was your husband there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5585082 SO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 
My husband - was home when my first baby was born, his mother was buried on the Wednesday and my wee girl was born on the Saturday. And he was at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid605028 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 And did he help at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5585082 SO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 He rean a - he went across for his sister and she came across.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid605028 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 
At that time when your first baby was born how long did you have to stay in bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5585082 SO  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13919541\charrsid12863516 
